	doi = {doi:10.1126/science.177.4052.850},
	abstract = {Presents a statistical configuration theory which proposes that the common mode of activity in massive numbers of neurons in anatomically extensive systems represents information about a learned experience. Different brain regions share a common mode during learning. When an experienced organism receives a novel and meaningless stimulus and generalization occurs, this new afferent input in a familiar context activates the representational system causing release of a common activity mode like that stored during the learning experience. Moreover, this released activity is not attributable to the numerous unspecific factors investigated, and seems to reflect the memory of that experience. The relationship between the temporal distribution of release of a specific waveshape and subsequent occurrence of the appropriate behavior was found to be highly nonrandom. Results of a series of experiments with 25 trained cats, and analogous data taken from studies with human Ss, are compatible with the proposed theory and are difficult to reconcile with switchboard and place theories of learning which lack comparable empirical evidence. Findings suggest that the subjective experience of remembering is correlated with the release of readout processes, and it is hypothesized that coherent temporal patterns in the average activity of anatomically extensive neural ensembles may constitute the neurophysiological basis of subjective experience. (135 ref.) {(PsycINFO} Database Record (c) 2009 {APA,} all rights reserved)},
